title: "Se7en"
rating: 0.1
review {
  direction {
    director {
      name: "David Fincher"
    }
    rating: "Great"
    comments: "The direction on a macroscale is great as he creates this dark and grimey environment that looks like hell on the surface; the direction on a microscale is very good as he uses tension well to raise the stakes in the interpersonal scenes; the storytelling is great as it uses such a captivating story to really draw you in, and uses tension well to help tell this story; he uses tension masterfully as it is integral in telling the story, setting the scene, and raising the stakes"
  }
  acting {
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Brad Pitt"
      }
      rating: "Pretty Good"
      comments: "Shows glimpses of being the star he will become as he shows command leading his scenes, but he definitely shows some inexperience"
    }
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Morgan Freeman"
      }
      rating: "Good"
      comments: "Shows his calm nature in his scenes as he is an experienced actor who helps those he acts with; has pretty good chemistry with Pitt; shows a range of emotions, and definitely changes his personality in the end to fit the scenario"
    }
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Gwyneth Paltrow"
      }
      rating: "Pretty Good"
      comments: "Plays dective's wife well and shows her concern for the situation and her husband"
    }
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "R. Lee Ermey"
      }
      rating: "Pretty Good"
      comments: "Plays the captain role well, but is less captivating than his 'Full Metal Jacket' role because of what is asked from him"
    }
    performance {
      actor {
        name: "Kevin Spacey"
      }
      rating: "Good"
      comments: "Shows so much subtly with very little time; truly captivating as he steals the scene with his menacing presense"
    }
    cast {
      rating: "Pretty Good"
      comments: "Every minor role plays their role well as they help build the tension and help tell the story"
    }
    rating: "Pretty Good to Good"
  }
  story {
    writer {
      name: "Andrew Kevin Walker"
    }
    rating: "Incredible"
    comments: "The concept is incredible as it uses the seven deadly sins as a blue-print to create such a captivating serial-killer film; the plot structure is very good as it uses the symmetry of a week to model the seven deadly sins murders; character writing is good as it has this buddy-cop dynamic between the seasoned vet and the newcomer, but the character that steals the show is John Doe as his omnious nature makes him such a menacing character"
  }
  screenplay {
    writer {
      name: "Andrew Kevin Walker"
    }
    rating: "Incredible"
    comments: "The dialogue is very sharp and well written, and there are many iconic lines; the humor helps lighten the tension in moments; the symbolism is great as the whole movie draws from parallels of the 7 deadly sins and works that stem from it; the foreshadowing is incredibly"
  }
  score {
    composer {
      name: "Howard Shore"
    }
    rating: "Pretty Good"
    comments: "A little overbearing at moments, but is essestinal in establsihign the tone"
  }
  cinematography {
    cinematographer {
      name: "Darius Khondji"
    }
    rating: "Great"
    comments: "Helps show the grime and dark nature of this underbelly; the lighting of this movie really makes this movie iconic"
  }
  editing {
    editor {
      name: "Richard Francis-Bruce"
    }
    rating: "Incredible"
    comments: "The film is put together like solving a murder mystery, as it feels like scenes of film-strips are stitched together to try and solve this crime; the uses of adding single frames is something Fincher is known for and is really integral to his story"
  }
  sound {
    rating: "Good"
    comments: "Helps build tension and used well in the action sequences"
  }
  production_design {
    rating: "Great"
    comments: "Helps show the grime and dark nature of this underbelly"
  }
  makeup {
